urrencies and blockchain technology has identified issues such as pricing abnormalities and bubble-like behavior, indicating that these new assets are highly speculative in nature, contain a growing number of legal abnormalities (such as the hacking of exchanges and broad theft of investor assets) and a growing number of significant regulatory issues. It is paramount that we investigate each of these issues in great detail to help to determine whether cryptocurrencies and blockchain technology merits consideration as a sustainable alternative investment asset. The handbook will be useful for specialist technical audiences such as legal, accounting and financial practices. It will also be beneficial for upper level masters and research students in economics, law, accounting, taxation, investment and portfolio management.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aBanks and bankingxTechnological innovations. 0aBlockchains (Databases). 0aCryptocurrencies. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Finance / General.2bisacsh  aAlternative Investments.  aBlockchain Technology.  aCryptocurrency.  aDigital Finance.  aFinancial Markets.1 aAdachi, Daisuke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAoyagi, Jun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAspris, Angelo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBouri, Elie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorbet, Shaen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorbet, Shaen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCumming, Douglas J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoley, Sean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGupta, Rangan, econtrib